A Node is an interface from which a number of DOM types inherit, and allows these various types to be treated (or tested) similarly.
  The following all inherit this interface and its methods and properties (though they may return null in particular cases where not relevant; or throw an exception when adding children to a node type for which no children can exist): Document, Element, Attr, CharacterData (which Text, Comment, and CDATASection inherit), ProcessingInstruction, DocumentFragment, DocumentType, Notation, Entity, EntityReference

name: NodeFilter
description: A NodeFilter is used to filter the nodes in a NodeIterator or TreeWalker. They don't know anything about the DOM or how to traverse nodes; they just know how to evaluate a single node against the provided filter.

name: NodeIterator
description: The NodeIterator object allows you to iterate over the members of a list of the nodes in a subtree of the DOM, in document order.

name: NodeList
description: NodeList objects are collections of nodes returned by Node.childNodes and the querySelectorAll method.

name: Notation
description: NOTE: This is not implemented in Mozilla

name: Notification
description: The notification object, which you create using the navigator.mozNotification object's createNotification() method, is used to configure and display desktop notifications to the user.

properties.name: onclick
properties.description: A function to call when the notification is clicked.

properties.name: onclose
properties.description: A function to call when the notification is dismissed.

name: PannerNode
description: The PannerNode interface represents the behavior of a signal in space. It is an AudioNode, that is an audio-processing module describing its position with a right-hand Cartesian coordinates, its movement using a velocity vector and its directionality using a directionality cone. A PannerNode always has exactly one input and one output: the input can be mono or stereo but the output is always stereo (2 channels).

properties.name: PannerNode.panningModel
properties.description:
Is an enumerated value determining which spatialization algorithm to use to position the audio in 3D space. The possible values are:
  • "equalpower", representing the equal-power panning algorithm, usually considered as simple and efficient;
  • "HRTF", rendering a stereo output and of higher quality than the previous one as it uses a convolution with measured impulse responses from human subjects. It is the default value.

properties.name: PannerNode.distanceModel
properties.description:
Is an enumerated value determining which algorithm to use to reduce the volume of the audio source as it moves away from the listeners. The possible values are:
  • "linear", a linear distance model calculating the gain induced by the distance according to: 1 - rolloffFactor * (distance - refDistance) / (maxDistance - refDistance).
  • "inverse", an inverse distance model calculating the gain induced by the distance according to: refDistance / (refDistance + rolloffFactor * (distance - refDistance)). This is the default value.
  • "exponential", an exponential distance model calculating hte gain induced by the distance according to: pow(distance / refDistance, -rolloffFactor)

properties.name: PannerNode.refDistance
properties.description: Is a double value representing the reference distance for reducing volume as source move further from the listener. This value is used by all distance model. Its default value is 1.

properties.name: PannerNode.maxDistance
properties.description: Is a double value representing the maximum distance between the source and the listener, after which the volume is no more reduced. This value is used only by the "linear" distance model. Its default value is 10000.

properties.name: PannerNode.rolloffFactor
properties.description: Is a double value describing how quickly the volume is reduced as the source moves away from listener. This value is used by all distance model. Its default value is 1.

properties.name: PannerNode.coneInnerAngle
properties.description: Is a double value describing the angle, in degrees, of the cone, inside of which there will be no volume reduction. Its default value is 360, suitable for a non-directional source.

properties.name: PannerNode.coneOuterAngle
properties.description: Is a double value describing the angle, in degrees, of the cone, outside of which the volume will be reduce by a constant value, defined by the coneOuterGain attribute. Its default value is 0.

properties.name: PannerNode.coneOuterGain
properties.description: Is a double value describing the amount of volume reduction outside of the cone defined by the coneOuterAngle attribute. Its default value is 0, meaning that no sound can be heard.

properties.name: Plugin.name

name: PowerManager
description: The PowerManager interface allow to explicitly control the part of the device that use power.

properties.description: This property allows to know if the device's screen is currently enabled (true). This property also controls the device's screen, so setting it to false will turn off the screen.

properties.name: PowerManager.screenBrightness
properties.description: This property defines how bright is the screen's backlight, on a scale from 0 (very dim) to 1 (full brightness). Setting this attribute modifies the screen's brightness.

properties.name: PowerManager.cpuSleepAllowed
properties.description: This property determines if the device's CPU will sleep after the screen is disabled. Setting this attribute to false will prevent the device entering suspend state.

name: ProcessingInstruction

name: ScriptProcessorNode
description: The ScriptProcessorNode interface allows the generation, processing, or analyzing of audio using JavaScript. It is an AudioNode, that is an audio-processing module, that is linked to two buffers, one containing the current input, one containing the output. An event, implementing the AudioProcessingEvent interface, is sent to the object each time the input buffer contains new data, and the event handler terminates when it has filled the output buffer with data.

properties.name: ScriptProcessNode.bufferSize
properties.description: Returns an integer representing both the input and output buffer size. It is a power of 2 value between 256 and 16384, included.

name: Selection
description: Selection is the class of the object returned by window.getSelection() and other methods. It represents the text selection in the greater page, possibly spanning multiple elements, when the user drags over static text and other parts of the page. For information about text selection in an individual text editing element, see Input, TextArea and document.activeElement which typically return the parent object returned from window.getSelection().

properties.name: anchorNode
properties.description: Returns the node in which the selection begins.

properties.name: anchorOffset
properties.description: Returns a number representing the offset of the selection's anchor within the anchorNode. If anchorNode is a text node, this is the number of characters within anchorNode preceding the anchor. If anchorNode is an element, this is the number of child nodes of the anchorNode preceding the anchor.

properties.name: focusNode
properties.description: Returns the node in which the selection ends.

properties.name: focusOffset
properties.description: Returns a number representing the offset of the selection's anchor within the focusNode. If focusNode is a text node, this is the number of characters within focusNode preceding the focus. If focusNode is an element, this is the number of child nodes of the focusNode preceding the focus.

properties.name: isCollapsed
properties.description: Returns a Boolean indicating whether the selection's start and end points are at the same position.

properties.name: rangeCount
properties.description: Returns the number of ranges in the selection.

description: The SVGStyleElement interface corresponds to the SVG <style> element.

name: SVGSVGElement
description: The SVGSVGElement interface provides access to the properties of <svg> elements, as well as methods to manipulate them. This interface contains also various miscellaneous commonly-used utility methods, such as matrix operations and the ability to control the time of redraw on visual rendering devices.

properties.name: x
properties.description: Corresponds to attribute x on the given <svg> element.

properties.name: y
properties.description: Corresponds to attribute y on the given <svg> element.

properties.name: width
properties.description: Corresponds to attribute width on the given <svg> element.

properties.name: height
properties.description: Corresponds to attribute height on the given <svg> element.

properties.name: contentScriptType
properties.description: Corresponds to attribute contentScriptType on the given <svg> element.

properties.name: contentStyleType
properties.description: Corresponds to attribute contentStyleType on the given <svg> element.

properties.name: viewport
properties.description: The position and size of the viewport (implicit or explicit) that corresponds to this <svg> element. When the browser is actually rendering the content, then the position and size values represent the actual values when rendering. The position and size values are unitless values in the coordinate system of the parent element. If no parent element exists (i.e., <svg> element represents the root of the document tree), if this SVG document is embedded as part of another document (e.g., via the HTML <object> element), then the position and size are unitless values in the coordinate system of the parent document. (If the parent uses CSS or XSL layout, then unitless values represent pixel units for the current CSS or XSL viewport.)

properties.name: pixelUnitToMillimeterX
properties.description: Size of a pixel units (as defined by CSS2) along the x-axis of the viewport, which represents a unit somewhere in the range of 70dpi to 120dpi, and, on systems that support this, might actually match the characteristics of the target medium. On systems where it is impossible to know the size of a pixel, a suitable default pixel size is provided.

properties.name: pixelUnitToMillimeterY
properties.description: Corresponding size of a pixel unit along the y-axis of the viewport.

properties.name: screenPixelToMillimeterX
properties.description: User interface (UI) events in DOM Level 2 indicate the screen positions at which the given UI event occurred. When the browser actually knows the physical size of a "screen unit", this attribute will express that information; otherwise, user agents will provide a suitable default value such as .28mm.

properties.name: screenPixelToMillimeterY
properties.description: Corresponding size of a screen pixel along the y-axis of the viewport.

properties.name: useCurrentView
properties.description: The initial view (i.e., before magnification and panning) of the current innermost SVG document fragment can be either the "standard" view (i.e., based on attributes on the <svg> element such as viewBox) or to a "custom" view (i.e., a hyperlink into a particular <view> or other element). If the initial view is the "standard" view, then this attribute is false. If the initial view is a "custom" view, then this attribute is true.

properties.name: currentView
properties.description:
The definition of the initial view (i.e., before magnification and panning) of the current innermost SVG document fragment. The meaning depends on the situation:
  • If the initial view was a "standard" view, then:
    • the values for viewBox, preserveAspectRatio and zoomAndPan within currentView will match the values for the corresponding DOM attributes that are on SVGSVGElement directly
    • the values for transform and viewTarget within currentView will be null
  • If the initial view was a link into a <view> element, then:
    • the values for viewBox, preserveAspectRatio and zoomAndPan within currentView will correspond to the corresponding attributes for the given <view> element
    • the values for transform and viewTarget within currentView will be null
  • If the initial view was a link into another element (i.e., other than a <view>), then:
    • the values for viewBox, preserveAspectRatio and zoomAndPan within currentView will match the values for the corresponding DOM attributes that are on SVGSVGElement directly for the closest ancestor <svg> element
    • the values for transform within currentView will be null
    • the viewTarget within currentView will represent the target of the link
  • If the initial view was a link into the SVG document fragment using an SVG view specification fragment identifier (i.e., #svgView(...)), then:
    • the values for viewBox, preserveAspectRatio, zoomAndPan, transform and viewTarget within currentView will correspond to the values from the SVG view specification fragment identifier

properties.name: currentTranslate
properties.description: On an outermost <svg> element, the corresponding translation factor that takes into account user "magnification".

properties.name: currentScale
properties.description: On an outermost <svg> element, this attribute indicates the current scale factor relative to the initial view to take into account user magnification and panning operations. DOM attributes currentScale and currentTranslate are equivalent to the 2x3 matrix [a b c d e f] = [currentScale 0 0 currentScale currentTranslate.x currentTranslate.y]. If "magnification" is enabled (i.e., zoomAndPan="magnify"), then the effect is as if an extra transformation were placed at the outermost level on the SVG document fragment (i.e., outside the outermost <svg> element).

description: The SVGTitleElement interface corresponds to the <title> element.

name: SVGTransform
description: SVGTransform is the interface for one of the component transformations within an SVGTransformList; thus, an SVGTransform object corresponds to a single component (e.g., scale(…) or matrix(…)) within a transform attribute.

properties.name: type
properties.description: The type of the value as specified by one of the SVG_TRANSFORM_* constants defined on this interface.

properties.name: angle
properties.description:
A convenience attribute for SVG_TRANSFORM_ROTATE, SVG_TRANSFORM_SKEWX and SVG_TRANSFORM_SKEWY. It holds the angle that was specified.

For SVG_TRANSFORM_MATRIX, SVG_TRANSFORM_TRANSLATE and SVG_TRANSFORM_SCALE, angle will be zero.

properties.name: matrix
properties.description:
The matrix that represents this transformation. The matrix object is live, meaning that any changes made to the SVGTransform object are immediately reflected in the matrix object and vice versa. In case the matrix object is changed directly (i.e., without using the methods on the SVGTransform interface itself) then the type of the SVGTransform changes to SVG_TRANSFORM_MATRIX.

  • For SVG_TRANSFORM_MATRIX, the matrix contains the a, b, c, d, e, f values supplied by the user.
  • For SVG_TRANSFORM_TRANSLATE, e and f represent the translation amounts (a=1, b=0, c=0 and d=1).
  • For SVG_TRANSFORM_SCALE, a and d represent the scale amounts (b=0, c=0, e=0 and f=0).
  • For SVG_TRANSFORM_SKEWX and SVG_TRANSFORM_SKEWY, a, b, c and d represent the matrix which will result in the given skew (e=0 and f=0).
  • For SVG_TRANSFORM_ROTATE, a, b, c, d, e and f together represent the matrix which will result in the given rotation. When the rotation is around the center point (0, 0), e and f will be zero.

name: SVGTransformable
description: Interface SVGTransformable contains properties and methods that apply to all elements which have attribute transform.

description: The SVGTransformList defines a list of SVGTransform objects.

name: SVGTSpanElement

properties.description: If the xlink:href attribute is being animated, contains the current animated root of the instance tree. If the xlink:href attribute is not currently being animated, contains the same value as instanceRoot. See description of SVGElementInstance to learn more about the instance tree.

name: SVGViewElement
description: The SVGViewElement interface provides access to the properties of <view> elements, as well as methods to manipulate them.

properties.name: viewTarget
properties.description: Corresponds to attribute viewTarget on the given <view> element. A list of DOMString values which contain the names listed in the viewTarget attribute. Each of the DOMString values can be associated with the corresponding element using the getElementById() method call.

name: SVGVKernElement
description: The SVGVKernElement interface corresponds to the <vkern> elements.

name: TCPSocket
description: Provides access to a raw TCP socket API in JavaScript.

name: Telephony
description: Provides support for dialing, answering, and managing phone calls on a device with telephony support.

properties.name: Telephony.active
properties.description: A TelephonyCall object indicating the call that is currently active. The active call is the one receiving input from the microphone and any tones generated using the Telephony.startTone() method.

properties.name: Telephony.calls
properties.description: An array of TelephonyCall objects, one for each call that is currently connected.

properties.name: Telephony.muted
properties.description: Set to true to mute the microphone or false to enable the microphone.

properties.name: Telephony.speakerEnabled
properties.description: Set to true to enable the speakerphone functionality or false to disable it.

name: TelephonyCall
description: Represents one telephone call, providing information about the call and offering mechanisms for controlling it and detecting changes to its status.

properties.name: TelephonyCall.number
properties.description: A string indicating the phone number corresponding to the call.

properties.name: TelephonyCall.state
properties.description: A string indicating the status of the call.

name: Text
description: In the DOM, the Text interface represents the textual content of an Element or Attr.  If an element has no markup within its content, it has a single child implementing Text that contains the element's text.  However, if the element contains markup, it is parsed into information items and Text nodes that form its children.

properties.name: text.isElementContentWhitespaceObsolete
properties.description:
Returns whether or not the text node contains only whitespace.  Read only.

Note: Do not use this property as it has been removed from the standard and is no longer implemented in recent browsers, like Firefox 10.

properties.name: text.wholeText
properties.description: Returns all text of all Text nodes logically adjacent to this node, concatenated in document order.

name: TimeRanges
description: The TimeRanges interface is used to represent a set of time ranges, primarily for the purpose of tracking which portions of media have been buffered when loading it for use by the <audio> and <video> elements.

properties.name: TimeRanges.length
properties.description: The number of time ranges represented by the time range object. Read only.

name: Touch
description: A Touch object represents a single point of contact between the user and a touch-sensitive interface device (which may be, for example, a touchscreen or a trackpad).

name: TouchEvent
description: A TouchEvent represents an event sent when the state of contacts with a touch-sensitive surface changes. This surface can be a touch screen or trackpad, for example. The event can describe one or more points of contact with the screen and includes support for detecting movement, addition and removal of contact points, and so forth.

name: TouchList
description: A TouchList represents a list of all of the points of contact with a touch surface; for example, if the user has three fingers on the screen (or trackpad), the corresponding TouchList would have one Touch object for each finger, for a total of three entries.

properties.name: TouchList.length
properties.description: The number of Touch objects in the TouchList.

name: TreeWalker
description: The TreeWalker object represents the nodes of a document subtree and a position within them.

name: TypeInfo
description: NOTE: This is not implemented in Mozilla

name: UIEvent
description: The DOM UIEvent represents simple user interface events.

properties.name: detail
properties.description: Detail about the event, depending on the type of event. Read only.

properties.name: view
properties.description: A view which generated the event. Read only.

name: UserDataHandler
description: When associating user data with a key on a node, Node.setUserData() can also accept, in its third argument, a handler which will be called when the object is cloned, imported, deleted, renamed, or adopted. Per the specification, exceptions should not be thrown in a UserDataHandler. In both document.importNode() and Node.cloneNode(), although user data is not copied over, the handler will be called.

name: UserProximityEvent
description: The UserProximityEvent indicates whether a nearby physical object is present by using the proximity sensor of a device.

properties.name: UserProximityEvent.near
properties.description: Indicates if the device has sensed a nearby physical object.

name: ValidityState
description: The DOM ValidityState interface represents the validity states that an element can be in, with respect to constraint validation. Together, they help explain why an element's value fails to validate, if it's not valid.

properties.name: customError
properties.description: The element's custom validity message has been set to a non-empty string by calling the element's setCustomValidity() method.

properties.name: patternMismatch
properties.description: The value does not match the specified pattern.

properties.name: rangeOverflow
properties.description: The value is greater than the maximum specified by the max attribute.

properties.name: rangeUnderflow
properties.description: The value is less than the minimum specified by the min attribute.

properties.name: stepMismatch
properties.description: The value does not fit the rules determined by the step attribute (that is, it's not evenly divisible by the step value).

properties.name: tooLong
properties.description:
The value exceeds the specified maxlength for HTMLInputElement or HTMLTextAreaElement objects.

Note: This will never be true in Gecko, because elements' values are prevented from being longer than maxlength.

properties.name: typeMismatch
properties.description: The value is not in the required syntax (when type is email or url).

properties.name: valid
properties.description: The element meets all constraint validations, and is therefore considered to be valid.

properties.name: valueMissing
properties.description: The element has a required attribute, but no value.

name: WebGLRenderingContext
description: WebGLRenderingContext objects expose the WebGLRenderingContext interface, the principal interface in WebGL which provides special properties and methods to manipulate the 3D content rendered in an HTML canvas element.

name: WebSocket
description: The WebSocket object provides the API for creating and managing a WebSocket connection to a server, as well as for sending and receiving data on the connection.

properties.name: binaryType
properties.description: A string indicating the type of binary data being transmitted by the connection. This should be either "blob" if DOM Blob objects are being used or "arraybuffer" if ArrayBuffer objects are being used.

properties.name: bufferedAmount
properties.description: The number of bytes of data that have been queued using calls to send() but not yet transmitted to the network. This value does not reset to zero when the connection is closed; if you keep calling send(), this will continue to climb. Read only.

properties.name: extensions
properties.description: The extensions selected by the server. This is currently only the empty string or a list of extensions as negotiated by the connection.

properties.name: onclose
properties.description: An event listener to be called when the WebSocket connection's readyState changes to CLOSED. The listener receives a CloseEvent named "close".

properties.name: onerror
properties.description: An event listener to be called when an error occurs. This is a simple event named "error".

properties.name: onmessage
properties.description: An event listener to be called when a message is received from the server. The listener receives a MessageEvent named "message".

properties.name: onopen
properties.description: An event listener to be called when the WebSocket connection's readyState changes to OPEN; this indicates that the connection is ready to send and receive data. The event is a simple one with the name "open".

properties.name: protocol
properties.description: A string indicating the name of the sub-protocol the server selected; this will be one of the strings specified in the protocols parameter when creating the WebSocket object.

properties.name: readyState
properties.description: The current state of the connection; this is one of the Ready state constants. Read only.

properties.name: url
properties.description: The URL as resolved by the constructor. This is always an absolute URL. Read only.

name: WheelEvent
description: The DOM WheelEvent represents events that occur due to the user moving a mouse wheel or similar input device.

properties.name: deltaX
properties.description: Horizontal scroll amount. Read only.

properties.name: deltaYdeltaY
properties.description: Vertical scroll amount. Read only.

properties.name: deltaZ
properties.description: Scroll amount for the z-axis. Read only.

properties.name: deltaMode
properties.description: Unit of delta values. See Delta modes for a list of permitted values. Read only.

name: Window
description: This section provides a brief reference for all of the methods, properties, and events available through the DOM window object. The window object implements the Window interface, which in turn inherits from the AbstractView interface. Some additional global functions, namespaces objects, and constructors, not typically associated with the window, but available on it, are listed in the JavaScript Reference.

properties.name: window.applicationCache
properties.description: An OfflineResourceList object providing access to the offline resources for the window.

properties.name: window.closed
properties.description: This property indicates whether the current window is closed or not.

properties.name: window.Components
properties.description: The entry point to many XPCOM features. Some properties, e.g. classes, are only available to sufficiently privileged code. Web code should not use this property.

properties.name: window.console
properties.description: Returns a reference to the console object providing access to the browser's debugging console.

properties.name: window.content
properties.description: Returns a reference to the content element in the current window. The variant with underscore is deprecated.

properties.name: window.controllers
properties.description: Returns the XUL controller objects for the current chrome window.

properties.name: window.crypto
properties.description: Returns the browser crypto object.

properties.name: window.defaultStatus
properties.description: Gets/sets the status bar text for the given window.

properties.name: window.dialogArguments
properties.description: Gets the arguments passed to the window (if it's a dialog box) at the time window.showModalDialog() was called. This is an nsIArray.

properties.name: window.directories
properties.description: Synonym of window.personalbar

properties.name: window.document
properties.description: Returns a reference to the document that the window contains.

properties.name: window.frameElement
properties.description: Returns the element in which the window is embedded, or null if the window is not embedded.

properties.name: window.frames
properties.description: Returns an array of the subframes in the current window.

properties.name: window.fullScreen
properties.description: This property indicates whether the window is displayed in full screen or not.

properties.name: window.globalStorage
properties.description:
Unsupported since Gecko 13 (Firefox 13). Use window.localStorage instead.
Was: Multiple storage objects that are used for storing data across multiple pages.

properties.name: window.history
properties.description: Returns a reference to the history object.

properties.name: window.innerHeight
properties.description: Gets the height of the content area of the browser window including, if rendered, the horizontal scrollbar.

properties.name: window.innerWidth
properties.description: Gets the width of the content area of the browser window including, if rendered, the vertical scrollbar.

properties.name: window.length
properties.description: Returns the number of frames in the window. See also window.frames.

properties.name: window.location
properties.description: Gets/sets the location, or current URL, of the window object.

properties.name: window.locationbar
properties.description: Returns the locationbar object, whose visibility can be toggled in the window.

properties.name: window.localStorage
properties.description: Returns a reference to the local storage object used to store data that may only be accessed by the origin that created it.

properties.name: window.menubar
properties.description: Returns the menubar object, whose visibility can be toggled in the window.

properties.name: window.messageManager
properties.description: Returns the message manager object for this window.

properties.name: window.mozAnimationStartTime
properties.description: The time in milliseconds since epoch at which the current animation cycle began.

properties.name: window.mozInnerScreenX
properties.description: Returns the horizontal (X) coordinate of the top-left corner of the window's viewport, in screen coordinates. This value is reported in CSS pixels. See mozScreenPixelsPerCSSPixel in nsIDOMWindowUtils for a conversion factor to adapt to screen pixels if needed.

properties.name: window.mozInnerScreenY
properties.description: Returns the vertical (Y) coordinate of the top-left corner of the window's viewport, in screen coordinates. This value is reported in CSS pixels. See mozScreenPixelsPerCSSPixel for a conversion factor to adapt to screen pixels if needed.

properties.name: window.mozPaintCount
properties.description: Returns the number of times the current document has been rendered to the screen in this window. This can be used to compute rendering performance.

properties.name: window.name
properties.description: Gets/sets the name of the window.

properties.name: window.navigator
properties.description: Returns a reference to the navigator object.

properties.name: window.opener
properties.description: Returns a reference to the window that opened this current window.

properties.name: window.outerHeight
properties.description: Gets the height of the outside of the browser window.

properties.name: window.outerWidth
properties.description: Gets the width of the outside of the browser window.

properties.name: window.pageXOffset
properties.description: An alias for window.scrollX.

properties.name: window.pageYOffset
properties.description: An alias for window.scrollY

properties.name: window.parent
properties.description: Returns a reference to the parent of the current window or subframe.

properties.name: window.performance
properties.description: Provides a hosting area for performance related attributes.

properties.name: window.personalbar
properties.description: Returns the personalbar object, whose visibility can be toggled in the window.

properties.name: window.pkcs11
properties.description: Formerly provided access to install and remove PKCS11 modules. Now this property is always null.

properties.name: window.returnValue
properties.description: The return value to be returned to the function that called window.showModalDialog() to display the window as a modal dialog.

properties.name: window.screen
properties.description: Returns a reference to the screen object associated with the window.

properties.name: window.screen.availTop
properties.description: Specifies the y-coordinate of the first pixel that is not allocated to permanent or semipermanent user interface features.

properties.name: window.screen.availLeft
properties.description: Returns the first available pixel available from the left side of the screen.

properties.name: window.screen.availHeight
properties.description: Specifies the height of the screen, in pixels, minus permanent or semipermanent user interface features displayed by the operating system, such as the Taskbar on Windows.

properties.name: window.screen.availWidth
properties.description: Returns the amount of horizontal space in pixels available to the window.

properties.name: window.screen.colorDepth
properties.description: Returns the color depth of the screen.

properties.name: window.screen.height
properties.description: Returns the height of the screen in pixels.

properties.name: window.screen.left
properties.description: Returns the current distance in pixels from the left side of the screen.

properties.name: window.screen.pixelDepth
properties.description: Gets the bit depth of the screen.

properties.name: window.screen.top
properties.description: Returns the distance from the top of the screen.

properties.name: window.screen.width
properties.description: Returns the width of the screen.

properties.name: window.screenX
properties.description: Returns the horizontal distance of the left border of the user's browser from the left side of the screen.

properties.name: window.screenY
properties.description: Returns the vertical distance of the top border of the user's browser from the top side of the screen.

properties.name: window.scrollbars
properties.description: Returns the scrollbars object, whose visibility can be toggled in the window.

properties.name: window.scrollMaxX
properties.description: The maximum offset that the window can be scrolled to horizontally.

properties.name: window.scrollMaxY
properties.description: (i.e., the document width minus the viewport width)

properties.name: window.scrollX
properties.description: The maximum offset that the window can be scrolled to vertically (i.e., the document height minus the viewport height).

properties.name: window.scrollY
properties.description: Returns the number of pixels that the document has already been scrolled horizontally.

properties.name: window.self
properties.description: Returns the number of pixels that the document has already been scrolled vertically.

properties.name: window.sessionStorage
properties.description: Returns an object reference to the window object itself.

properties.name: window.sidebar
properties.description: A storage object for storing data within a single page session.

properties.name: window.status
properties.description: Returns a reference to the window object of the sidebar.

properties.name: window.statusbar
properties.description: Gets/sets the text in the statusbar at the bottom of the browser.

properties.name: window.toolbar
properties.description: Returns the statusbar object, whose visibility can be toggled in the window.

properties.name: window.top
properties.description: Returns the toolbar object, whose visibility can be toggled in the window.

properties.name: window.URL
properties.description: Returns a reference to the topmost window in the window hierarchy. This property is read only.

properties.name: window.window
properties.description: A DOM URL object, which provides the window.URL.createObjectURL() and window.URL.revokeObjectURL() methods.

properties.name: window[0]
properties.description: Returns a reference to the current window.

name: Worker
description: Workers are background tasks that can be easily created and can send messages back to their creators. Creating a worker is as simple as calling the Worker() constructor, specifying a script to be run in the worker thread.

properties.name: onmessage
properties.description: An event listener that is called whenever a MessageEvent with type message bubbles through the worker. The message is stored in the event's data member.

properties.name: onerror
properties.description: An event listener that is called whenever an ErrorEvent with type error bubbles through the worker.

name: XMLHttpRequest
description: XMLHttpRequest is a JavaScript object that was designed by Microsoft and adopted by Mozilla, Apple, and Google. It's now being standardized in the W3C. It provides an easy way to retrieve data at a URL. Despite its name, XMLHttpRequest can be used to retrieve any type of data, not just XML, and it supports protocols other than HTTP (including file and ftp).

properties.name: onreadystatechange
properties.description:
A JavaScript function object that is called whenever the readyState attribute changes. The callback is called from the user interface thread.

Warning: This should not be used with synchronous requests and must not be used from native code.

properties.name: readyState
properties.description:
The state of the request:

Value State Description
0 UNSENT open()has not been called yet.
1 OPENED send()has not been called yet.
2 HEADERS_RECEIVED send() has been called, and headers and status are available.
3 LOADING Downloading; responseText holds partial data.
4 DONE The operation is complete.

properties.name: response
properties.description: The response entity body according to responseType, as an ArrayBuffer, Blob, Document, JavaScript object (for "json"), or string. This is null if the request is not complete or was not successful.

properties.name: responseText
properties.description: The response to the request as text, or null if the request was unsuccessful or has not yet been sent.

properties.name: responseType
properties.description:
Can be set to change the response type.

Value Data type of response property
"" (empty string) String (this is the default)
"arraybuffer" ArrayBuffer
"blob" Blob
"document" Document
"json" JavaScript object, parsed from a JSON string returned by the server
"text" String
"moz-blob" Used by Firefox to allow retrieving partial Blob data from progress events. This lets your progress event handler start processing data while it's still being received. Requires Gecko 12.0
"moz-chunked-text"

Similar to "text", but is streaming. This means that the value in response, is only available during dispatch of the "progress" event and only contains the data received since the last "progress" event.

When response is accessed during a "progress" event it contains a string with the data. Otherwise it returns null.

This mode currently only works in Firefox. Requires Gecko 9.0
"moz-chunked-arraybuffer"

Similar to "arraybuffer", but is streaming. This means that the value in response, is only available during dispatch of the "progress" event and only contains the data received since the last "progress" event.

When response is accessed during a "progress" event it contains a string with the data. Otherwise it returns null.

This mode currently only works in Firefox. Requires Gecko 9.0
Note: Starting with Gecko 11.0 (Firefox 11.0 / Thunderbird 11.0 / SeaMonkey 2.8), as well as WebKit build 528, these browsers no longer let you use the responseType attribute when performing synchronous requests. Attempting to do so throws an NS_ERROR_DOM_INVALID_ACCESS_ERR exception. This change has been proposed to the W3C for standardization.

properties.name: responseXML
properties.description:
The response to the request as a DOM Document object, or null if the request was unsuccessful, has not yet been sent, or cannot be parsed as XML or HTML. The response is parsed as if it were a text/xml stream. When the responseType is set to "document" and the request has been made asynchronously, the response is parsed as it were a text/html stream.

Note: If the server doesn't apply the text/xml Content-Type header, you can use overrideMimeType()to force XMLHttpRequest to parse it as XML anyway.

properties.name: status
properties.description: The status of the response to the request. This is the HTTP result code (for example, status is 200 for a successful request).

properties.name: statusText
properties.description: The response string returned by the HTTP server. Unlike status, this includes the entire text of the response message ("200 OK", for example).

properties.name: timeout
properties.description:
The number of milliseconds a request can take before automatically being terminated. A value of 0 (which is the default) means there is no timeout. Requires Gecko 12.0

Note: You may not use a timeout for synchronous requests with an owning window.

properties.name: upload
properties.description: The upload process can be tracked by adding an event listener to upload.

properties.name: withCredentials
properties.description:
Indicates whether or not cross-site Access-Control requests should be made using credentials such as cookies or authorization headers. The default is false.

Note: This never affects same-site requests.
Note: Starting with Gecko 11.0 (Firefox 11.0 / Thunderbird 11.0 / SeaMonkey 2.8), Gecko no longer lets you use the withCredentials attribute when performing synchronous requests. Attempting to do so throws an NS_ERROR_DOM_INVALID_ACCESS_ERR exception.

name: XMLHttpRequestEventTarget
description: XMLHttpRequestEventTarget is the interface that describes the event handlers you can implement in an object that will handle events for an XMLHttpRequest.

properties.name: onabort
properties.description: The function to call when a request is aborted.

properties.name: onerror
properties.description: The function to call when a request encounters an error.

properties.name: onload
properties.description: The function to call when an HTTP request returns after successfully loading content.

properties.name: onloadstart
properties.description: A function that gets called when the HTTP request first begins loading data.

properties.name: onprogress
properties.description: A function that is called periodically with information about the progress of the request.

properties.name: ontimeout
properties.description: A function that is called if the event times out; this only happens if a timeout has been previously established by setting the value of the XMLHttpRequest object's timeout attribute.

properties.name: onloadend
properties.description: A function that is called when the load is completed, even if the request failed.
